        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Feb 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I have had a letter from M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Mason, requesting me as a favour to pay my subscription half-yearly &amp; at the dates of the 16<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of Feb. &amp; 16<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of August.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Would you kindly do this for me.— Though on reflexion, I do not see, how you can earlier than Lady Day &amp; Michaelmas.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Perhaps you will be so good as to pay as soon as you receive the Rent &amp; then it will be somewhere near the dates requested.</p>
<p>I hope that you will excuse this trouble &amp; believe me, My dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | C. Darwin</p>
<p>You can, if you like keep back 5£ next Lady Day &amp; thus pay as M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Mason requests.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.4 Lady Day] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘Michaelmas &amp;’</note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD subscribed £5 each year for the support of Beesby School (see CD’s Account Book and Investment Book (Down House MSS)). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3204.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Payne Mason</ref>, rector of Beesby, was presumably responsible for collecting the subscriptions to Beesby School.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">March 25, the day of the Annunciation of the Virgin Mary, and 10 October, which were two of the traditional ‘quarter-days’ of the business year, when rents were paid.</note>
        </div>        
            
